@node "about" "About"

  @{b}Introduction@{ub}

    PowerView3d is a viewer for LightWave objects. It isn't yet another
  program, which draws objects as wireframe or in the best case as flat
  shaded. Thanks to use of a PowerPC processor it is able to render them
  as reflection mapped in realtime.

  It is shareware. See @{"registration" link register} for details.

  THIS SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED "AS IS" WITHOUT WARRANTIES ON PERFORMANCE.
  THE AUTHOR CAN'T BE HELD LIABLE FOR ANY DAMAGE CAUSED BY THE PROGRAM.

  tested on:

    - blizzard603e/166-040/25-32ram-aga
    - blizzard603e/200-040/25-32ram-aga
    - blizzard603e/240-040/25-64ram-aga
    - cyberstorm604e/233-040/40-64ram-cybervision64/3d


  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "register" "Registration"

  @{b}Registration@{ub}

  An unregistered version has currently only one limitation - it can view
  objects with no more than 2000 faces only.

  The registration fee is only USD 10 or DM 15. The fee may rise in future.

  Registered users will recieve a keyfile which enables the missing feature.
  This keyfile will work with all future versions of PowerView3D, so you
  can always download the most recent freely distributable version and use
  it without limitations if you are registered user.

  In order to register PowerView3D you have to send @{"me" link author} your name, address,
  e-mail and of course the registration fee. Please, make a note how do you
  want to recieve your personalized keyfile (by e-mail or snail-mail?).

  If you wish to get your keyfile by snail-mail, remember to add DM 3 or
  USD 2 to the fee for disk and shipping.

  The keyfile must be placed in PV3D: directory. Its name is PV3D.key

  It is YOUR PERSONALIZED KEYFILE so better don't gove it to your friends
  and don't upload it to one of those well known servers! Remember that it
  is up to you whether PowerView3D will be developed in the future or not.
  I guarantee I won't stop developing it and I will do my best, if several
  people register it.

  Remember to put the cash in non transparent paper or sth like that.
  If it is possible send me a mail before sending money.

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "req" "Requirements"

  @{b}Requirements@{ub}

    - an Amiga computer with OS 3.0+
    - a @{b}PowerPC@{ub} processor
    - a graphics card supported by @{b}CyberGraphX@{ub} or an AGA chipset
    - ppc.library

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "installation" "Installation"

  @{b}Installation@{ub}

  In order to install you only need to decompress the archive to your hd and
  create the assign PV3D: to the directory PowerView3D.

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "usage" "Usage"

  @{b}Starting from CLI@{ub}

  PowerView3D <options> FILE plik1 plik2 ...

  options:

    MODE=n
      Mode of drawing:
        0 - WIREFRAME
        1 - FLAT SHADED
        2 - GOURAUD
        3 - REFLECTIONMAP

    DRAGMODE=n
      Mode of drawing while rotation, moving and zooming:
        0 - bez zmian
        1 - BOUNDING BOX
        2 - WIREFRAME
        3 - FLAT SHADED

    REFMAP=nazwa
      Name of the @{"texture" link textures} to be used as reflectionmap
      (the name must not contain spaces)

  example:

    PowerView3d MODE=5 DRAGMODE=1 REFMAP=metal FILE objects:cow objects:triceratops

  You have to use @{b}ppcrun@{ub} or similar program, if you haven't run
  the @{b}elfloadseg@{ub} patch.

  Remember to increase the @{"stack" link stack} size before running the program.
  20000 bytes would be enough.
  
  @{b}Key control@{ub}

  SPACE           next object
  BACKSPACE       previous object
  1               wireframe
  2               flat shaded
  3               gouraud
  4               reflectionmap
  5               not changed
  6               bounding box
  7               wireframe
  8               flat shaded
  +               zoom in
  -               zoom out
  c               center pivot point on/off
  i               informations on/off
  ARROWS          move object
  ESC             quit

  @{b}Mouse control@{ub}
  LMB             rotate object
  RMB             zoom object


  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "textures" "textures"

  @{b}Textures@{ub}

  The textures are placed in the directory /@{b}data@{ub}.
  Texture size - 256x256 (chunky8bit grayscale format).

  To prepare your own texture you have to use converter to chunky format
  such as @{b}ArtPro@{ub}.

  @{" back " link usage}
@endnode

@node "stack" "stack"

  Increase of the stack size is performed by the AmigaDOS command

    @{b}stack@{ub} n

  n - requested stack size

  @{" back " link usage}
@endnode

@node "config" "Preferences program"

  @{b}Preferences program@{ub}
  
    @{b}draw mode@{ub}
    Mode of drawing.

    @{b}mode while dragging@{ub}
    Mode of drawing while rotation, moving and zooming.

    @{b}quality@{ub}
    Drawing quality in gouraud and refmap modes.

    @{b}center pivot point@{ub}
    As the name suggests it turns on/off centering of pivot point.

    @{b}show info@{ub}
    Turns on/off showing information about an object (name, number of faces
    and points).

    @{b}screen ModeID@{ub}
    Brings up a screenmode requester. Despite it is possible to choose any
    available resolution, the screen is always 320 width and 240 height.
    In the near future there will be a possibility to open screen of any size.
    Only 8bit modes are available now.

    @{b}Save@{ub}
    Saves the preferences to file ENVARC:PowerView3D.prefs

    @{b}Use@{ub}
    Saves the preferences to file ENV:PowerView3D.prefs


    The AGA version has its own preferences program - PowerView3D_AGA_Prefs.
    Preferences are then saved to file ENVARC:PowerView3D_AGA.prefs

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "history" "history"

  @{b}history@{ub}

  0.1-0.8b (6.09-8.11.1998)
    Internal beta versions.

  0.9 (10.11.1998)
    First released version:
      - it doesn't take into consideration doublesided flag (draws every
        object as singlesided), so some objects could look strange
      - 'good quality' mode isn't finished yet
      - no window display and no support for 15/16/24 bit modes yet

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "bugs" "bugs"

  @{b}bîëdy@{ub}

  - run exactly with a three command line parameters hangs up

  - wireframe mode isn't reliable at all yet (especially when object is
    zoomed in)

  - bounding box sometimes disappears

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

@node "future" "Future"

  @{b}future@{ub}

    - bug fixing
    - 15/16/24 bit mode (on CyberGraphX)
    - window display on Workbench or any other public screen
    - LightWave plug-in based on the PV3D, which shows the preview in window
      on LW screen (CGX) or separate screen (AGA)
    - real-mode - considering all attributes of an object (textures, bump
      maps, reflection maps, surface colour, specular and reflectivity
      level, transparency, etc.), useful with Modeler and Layout plug-ins
      announced above
    - support for the other popular object formats
    - version for WarpOS or other more stable system than ppc.library
    - support for CyberGL or other port of OpenGL
    - support for Permedia2
    - and of course more speed (the program will be several times faster
      than it is now)

  I also ask you for your feedback - write what do you wish to see in future
  versions of PV3D.

  @{" back " link Main}
@endnode

